<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9666066535761></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9666066535761><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=6&mid=9666066535761>RE: Soloing...</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=6&mid=9666066535761#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 9:50 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>While blinding and rooting are fine tactics for emergencies, Paladins really aren't a solo class. Remember that Paladins have no DD spells for living creatures before level 49, so as a melee class they can be smacked down hard by casting classes, even high green mobs at higher levels. The best thing for a paladin to solo is Undead, just beware that many of the crypts where Undead lurk have 3 or 4 mobs close together.<br><br>With all of that in mind, Paladins are actually a very group-friendly class, and in a full group with a cleric and enchanter, they can fight virtually non-stop all day long. I have found I make 1 bubble of xp an hour in such a group, even with members 4 levels above me. This is far better than the xp I make solo, which is about 1 bubble per 2-3 hours due to the higher downtime without a dedicated healer. Personally I find Paladin soloing to be very boring. Perhaps people like to try solo because of the lack of dependable clerics and enchanters?<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
